# TheBreakRoom

A real, permanently-hosted version of TheBreakRoom, backed by a Supabase database
instead of Claude's artifact-only storage.

## What changed from the Claude artifact version

- `src/App.jsx` — the app itself, unchanged from the Claude artifact.
- `src/storage.js` — **new**. Replaces `window.storage` with real calls to a
  Supabase table (`breakroom_kv_store`) so data actually persists on the internet.
- `src/main.jsx` — loads `storage.js` before the app renders.
- Everything else is standard Vite + React scaffolding.

## Deploying (recommended: Vercel)

1. Push this whole folder to a GitHub repo (see below if you haven't already).
2. Go to https://vercel.com, sign in with your GitHub account.
3. Click **Add New → Project**, pick this repo.
4. Vercel auto-detects Vite. Don't change any settings — click **Deploy**.
5. In a minute or two you'll get a real URL like `thebreakroom.vercel.app`.
6. Every time you push to GitHub, Vercel rebuilds and updates the live site automatically.

You can later add a custom domain for free under the project's Settings → Domains.

## Pushing this folder to GitHub (if you haven't yet)

From a terminal, inside this folder:

```
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO.git
git push -u origin main
```

(Replace the URL with your actual empty GitHub repo's URL — create one first at
github.com/new if you don't have it yet.)

## Alternative: GitHub Pages

Works too, but needs one extra step since Pages serves static files with no
build step of its own. Easiest way: use GitHub Actions to build on every push.
Vercel is simpler for a first deploy — switch to this later if you want
everything to live entirely on GitHub's infrastructure.

## About the database

This connects to a Supabase project (already set up) using its public "anon" key,
which is safe to ship in client-side code — it only allows what the database's
Row Level Security policies permit. Right now that policy allows anyone with the
key to read/write, matching the app's original design: this is a workplace
convenience tool with a phone+PIN gate, not a bank-grade security model. If that
ever needs to change, it happens on the Supabase side, not in this code.

## Local development

```
npm install
npm run dev
```
